window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2002>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2002","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES~~FLUID AT REST : EQUILIBRIUM OF BODIES: ARCHIMEDES\u2019 PRINCIPLE","question":"Using the diagrams below as a guide, carry out the following instructions.  (i) Pivot the metre rule, which has been drilled at the 50 cm mark, horizontally on the knife edge.    (ii) Suspend the object marked m at the 10 cm mark of the metre rule.  (iii) Suspend a 100 g mass on the other side of the knife edge and adjust the position of the mass until the metre rule balances horizontally as shown in diagram 1 above.  (iv) Read and record the distances, x, of m from the pivot and y1, of the 100 g mass from the pivot.  (v) Repeat the procedure for four other positions of m at the 10, 15, 20, 25 and 30 cm marks. In each case, keep the position of the knife edge fixed and adjust the position of the 100 g mass until the metre rule balances horizontally.  (vi) Also repeat the procedure with m completely immersed in water contained in a beaker and suspended at the 10, 15, 20, 25 and 30 cm marks of the metre rule respectively. In each case, adjust the position of the 100 g mass until the metre rule balances horizontally, then read and record the new distance y2 of the 100 g mass from the pivot.  (vii) Evaluate y1 - y2 in each case. Tabulate your readings.  (viii) Plot a graph of y1 on the vertical axis against y1 - y2 on the horizontal axis.  (ix) Determine the slope of the graph  (x) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/Nm(cm)x(cm)y1(cm)y2cmy1 - y2 (cm)110.0040.0020.6017.203.40215.0035.0018.1015.502.60320.0030.0015.5013.402.10425.0025.0012.8011.101.70530.0020.0010.309.001.30        slope = = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 20.3\u2212113.2\u22121.3\\frac{20.3-11}{3.2-1.3}3.2\u22121.320.3\u221211\u200b = 9319\\frac{93}{19}1993\u200b = 4.89    Precautions:  1. I ensured that the mass m was completely immersed in water without touching the sides or bottom of the container, to obtain accurate measurements.  2. I made sure that the metre rule balanced horizontally or was in equilibrium under parallel forces before taking my readings","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2002>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2002","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CENTRE OF GRAVITY AND STABILITY","question":"Explain what it is meant by the centre of gravity of a body and state how it is related to the stability of the body.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The center of gravity of a body is the point at which the entire weight of the body is considered to act, regardless of its orientation. It represents the average location of the gravitational force acting on the body. For uniform objects, this point often coincides with the geometric center, but for irregularly shaped objects, the center of gravity may lie outside the physical body.    The stability of a body is directly related to the position of its center of gravity. A low center of gravity increases stability, as it makes the body less likely to tip over when subjected to external forces. Conversely, a high center of gravity decreases stability, making the body more prone to tipping. A body is in stable equilibrium when a slight displacement causes it to return to its original position, which happens when the center of gravity remains within the base of support. If the center of gravity moves outside this base, the body becomes unstable and may topple.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2002>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2002","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"State the conditions of equilibrium for a body acted upon by a number of co-planar parallel forces.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The conditions of equilibrium for a body acted upon by a number of co-planar parallel forces are:    1. The algebraic sum of the forces is zero: This means that the total upward forces must equal the total downward forces.  2. The algebraic sum of the moments of the forces about any point in the plane is zero: This means that the clockwise and anticlockwise moments of the forces must balance each other out.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2002>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2002","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"Using the diagram above as a guide, carry out the following instructions.  (i) Fix a plane sheet of paper on the drawing board.  (ii) Place the rectangular glass prism on the paper and trace its outline, ABCD. Remove the prism.  (iii) Draw a normal NMP to meet AB and DC at M and P respectively such that |AM| = |DP| = 2.0 cm.  (iv) Trace the ray PQ with two pins. P1 and P2, at P and Q respectively such that angle MPQ = i = 5&#176;.  (v) Replace the prism on its outline. Trace the emergent ray with two other pins P3 and P4 such that they lie in a straight line with P2 and the image of P1 viewed through the glass prism  (vi) Measure and record \u03b8, the angle between the emergent ray and face AB of the glass prism  (vii) Evaluate cos \u03b8 and sin i.  (viii) Repeat the procedure for four other values of i = 10\u00b0, 15\u00b0, 20\u00b0 and 25\u00b0. Tabulate your readings.  (ix) Plot a graph of cos \u03b8 on the vertical axis against sin i on the horizontal axis.  (x) Determine the slope of the graph.  (xi) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results. [ Attach your traces to your answer booklet ].","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/Ni\u00b0\u03b8cos \u03b8sin i15810.1560.087210740.2760.174315690.3580.259420610.4840.342525510.6290.423        slope = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 0.6\u22120.20.4125\u22120.125\\frac{0.6-0.2}{0.4125-0.125}0.4125\u22120.1250.6\u22120.2\u200b = 3223\\frac{32}{23}2332\u200b = 1.39    Precautions:  1. I avoided parallax error by ensuring my eye was level with the scale when taking angle readings on the protractor.    2. I ensured that the glass prism was placed properly on the drawing paper, with all edges accurately traced for precise measurements of the angles of incidence and refraction.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2002>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2002","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"State the laws of refraction of light.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The incident ray, the refracted ray, and the normal at the point of incidence are all in the same plane. This means that the light rays and the normal line lie in a single flat surface. \u00a0     The ratio of the sine of the angle of incidence to the sine of the angle of refraction is constant for any two given media. This constant is known as the refractive index. Mathematically, it can be expressed as: \u00a0   n = sin\u2061(i)sin\u2061(r)\\frac{\\sin{\\left(i\\right)}}{\\sin{\\left(r\\right)}}sin(r)sin(i)\u200b","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2002>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2002","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"Explain what is meant by the statement  the refractive index of a material is 1.65 .","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The statement \"the refractive index of a material is 1.65\" means that light travels 1.65 times slower in that material compared to how it travels in a vacuum. In other words, the ratio of the speed of light in a vacuum to the speed of light in the material is 1.65. The refractive index (n) quantifies how much the light ray bends when it enters the material from another medium, such as air. A higher refractive index indicates a greater reduction in the speed of light and more bending.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2002>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2002","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"(i) Measure and record the length XY of the resistance wire provided.  (ii) Connect the circuit shown in the diagram above.  (iii) With R = 0 \u03a9, close the key, K. Read and record the current Io and the voltage drop Vo across the resistance wire.  (iv) Setting R = 1 \u03a9, close the key. Read and record the current, I and the corresponding voltage drop, V across the wire.  (v) Repeat the procedure for five other values of R = 5, 10, 20, 40 and 60 \u03a9. Tabulate your readings.  (vi) Plot a graph of V on the vertical axis against I on the horizontal axis.  (vii) Determine the slope of the graph.  (viii) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"XY = 100 cm    S/NR(\u03a9)I(A)V(volt)11.000.152.6525.000.152.65310.000.101.85420.000.081.40540.000.060.90660.000.040.07        slope = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 2.6\u22120.40.1425\u22120.0425\\frac{2.6-0.4}{0.1425-0.0425}0.1425\u22120.04252.6\u22120.4\u200b = 22 V/A    Precautions:  1. I ensured proper contact and accurate connections in the circuit to prevent resistance at the joints, which could affect the reliability of the measurements.    2. I opened the key plug when taking readings to prevent any unnecessary current flow that could interfere with the accuracy of the recorded values or cause overheating.    3. I avoided parallax error by aligning my eyes directly with the scale of the measuring instruments, such as the ammeter and voltmeter, to ensure accurate readings.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2002>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2002","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY~~ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CONDUCTION THROUGH MATERIALS","question":"Mention and state the law on which the experiment in 3(a) is based.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The experiment in 3(a) is based on Ohm's Law, which states that the current (I) flowing through a conductor between two points is directly proportional to the voltage (V) across the two points, provided the temperature remains constant. This relationship can be expressed mathematically as:    V = I \u00d7 R    where R is the resistance of the conductor. This law indicates that if the voltage increases, the current will also increase proportionally, assuming the resistance remains unchanged.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2002>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2002","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : RESISTIVITY AND CONDUCTIVITY","question":"A piece of resistance wire of diameter 0.20 mm and resistance 7 \u03a9 has resistivity of  8.8 \u00d7 10-7 \u03a9m, calculate the length of the wire. [&#960; = 227\\frac{22}{7}722\u200b]    (Provide your answer with the the S.I unit and to 2 decimal places e.g 123.123 N)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"R = \u03c1lA\\frac{\u03c1l}{A}A\u03c1l\u200b    A = \u03c0r2 = \u03c0 (d2)2\\left(\\frac{d}{2}\\right)^{2}(2d\u200b)2    = 227\\frac{22}{7}722\u200b \u00d7 (0.2\u00d710\u221232)2\\left(\\frac{0.2\u00d710^{-3}}{2}\\right)^{2}(20.2\u00d710\u22123\u200b)2 = 0.314 \u00d7 10-7 m2    l = RA\u03c1\\frac{RA}{\u03c1}\u03c1RA\u200b = 7\u00d70.314\u00d710\u221278.8\u00d710\u22127\\frac{7\u00d70.314\u00d710^{-7}}{8.8\u00d710^{-7}}8.8\u00d710\u221277\u00d70.314\u00d710\u22127\u200b = 0.25 m","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];